  <div class="ct">
  
<p>How are dying stars a metaphor the extremification of the GOP?</p>
<p>- &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; they spend their lives feeding on and spewing hot gases;</p>
<p>- &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; their structure and existence always represents a contradiction in that it consists of a balance between great opposing qualities or forces: one force’s proclivity is to contract and pull in on itself and hoard energy and mass; the other force wants to expand outward and belch its gaseous contents all over creation, trespassing on others' realms;</p>
<p>- &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; to maintain a steady output of energy, they must consume themselves from within;</p>
<p>- &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; as they age they become unstable, violently blowing off their various lighter constituencies, setting up a series of catastrophic and future (and futile) self-defeating events for themselves;</p>
<p>- &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; the great opposing forces can be sustained for a long time when held in balance, but they cannot tolerate this contradiction forever, especially if one of the forces becomes stronger than the other;</p>
<p>- &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; at a critical point for the aging body the contracting force prevails over the expansive force and in one great shift enormous amounts of the mass collapses in towards the center, whilst</p>
<p>- &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; another larger constituency is ejected away from the star forever, and will eventually create clumps of &nbsp;mass elsewhere; the less-dense materials are flung out and form new coalitions of and by gravitational influence;</p>
<p>- &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; only the core of the original body is left, consisting solely of its most dense constituents; in fact, the collapse itself produces new matter even more dense than had ever existed before;</p>
<p>- &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; the final collapsed center of the dying star may reach temperatures of hundreds of millions of degrees while at the same time gravitationally sucking down even much of its own light - which is a way of saying that it produces far more heat than light;</p>
<p>- &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; cores of the greatest densities become black holes, exiting the visible universe and soon governing ing themselves under completely different and idiosyncratic laws of physics and gravitational phenomena; the extreme density of black holes warp both time and space, bending and distorting all light quanta that may stray near them; an accretion disk surrounds the dense core, pulling resources from smaller bodies in its sphere of influence, inexorably fattening as it gorges on lighter-weight bodies; their now infinitely dense qualities are unseen, though those bodies with the greatest resources still furtively affect important matter(s) from a distance.</p>
<p>- &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; black holes and other ultra-dense bodies suck gas and other matter from lighter formerly-stable conservative bodies, gorging on them insatiably and inexorably and greedily feasting on their energy and matter for no other purpose than to expand endlessly, mindlessly...<br /></p>

  </div>
