  <a href="/user/uid:67799">417els</a>, <a href="/user/uid:235580">a2nite</a>, <a href="/user/uid:330318">JerryNA</a>
    </dd>
  
</dl></div>

  

  <div class="ct">
  
<p>Stossel thinks that the &nbsp;mere adequacy of private efforts were enough to condemn FDR for insturive intervention in the Great Depression.</p>
<p>In 1929, the Gross National Product was $101.6 billion (Not adjusted for inflation). In 1933, the GNP had fallen to $53 billion. That's a shortfall of $48 B. Using a multiplier of 3.5 (a standard economic assumption), Roosevelt would have needed new spending on the order of $13.9 annually to bring the economy back to what it was. Until World War II drove spending to new heights, FDR never spent more than $8.8 total for any year.</p>
<p>Now, picture two scenarios. In the one, Roosevelt had done even less. In the other, FDR had spent that 13.9 on home front preparedness projects--the St. Lawrence Seaway, railroad rebuilding, highway and bridge construction, etc. Wouldn't most people prefer the second scenario?</p>

  </div>
